{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} '''Continuous monitoring and adaptive control''' (CMAC) is a category of [[stormwater]] [[Best management practice for water pollution|best management practice]] that allows for a wider range of operation of [[detention pond|detention]] and [[retention pond|retention]] ponds. CMAC systems typically consist of a [[piezometer|water level sensor]], an [[butterfly valve|actuated valve]], and an internet connection.<ref>{{cite journal |authors=Jamie Lefkowitz, Alexa Sarmanian, and Marcus Quigley |title=Continuous monitoring and adaptive control—the internet of things transforms stormwater management |url=http://www.newea.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/NEWEA-Journal_Spr16.pdf#page=25 |work=Journal of the New England Water Environment Association |issn=1077-3002 |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=44–51 |date=Spring 2016}}</ref>
Specific applications of CMAC include flood protection, water quality treatment, water reuse, and channel protection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Advancements in Monitoring and RealTime Control Technology Result in Improved Stormwater Management |url=http://www.ohstormwaterconference.com/wp-content/uploads/2016-presentations/F2A-2Monitoring&ControlTechLefkowitzTootLevy.pdf |work=Ohio Stormwater Conference |accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref>
